issue_body:
I am using excel-builder.js library to create the excel data and FileSaver.js to save this file.
Below is my code for saving: 

testDataWorkbook.addWorksheet(testData);

saveAs(ExcelBuilder.createFile(testDataWorkbook, {
    type: "blob"
}), "test.xlsx");

Which works just fine in chrome and IE.
The problem I am getting with Firefox is while doing "Open with" the file which gets created is 
"test.xlsx.zip" which then throws a warning of different format than specified by the file extension.

Any help on the issue is much appreciated.

If I have this code: 
```
from selenium import webdriver

from mockito import mock, when


class ClassName(object):

    driver = None

    def create_driver(self, browser):
        if browser == 'chrome':
            self.driver = webdriver.Chrome()
        else:
            self.driver = webdriver.Firefox()

    def find_element(self, selector):
        element = self.driver.find_element_by_xpath(selector)
        if element:
            print 'Do something complex which I want to test'


x = ClassName()
when(x.driver).find_element_by_xpath('//dvi').thenReturn(mock())

```
Then I could not figure out an easy way to mock the  `element = self.driver.find_element_by_xpath(selector)` line.  I did try several ways with `when` or other ways to define the `driver`, but all of them ended with different type of errors. Usually with `AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'find_element_by_xpath'` How the code should be changed that the mocking would work?

I'm hacking around with django-social-auth and a custom user model and had the following issue.

I have my custom user model defined in SOCIAL_AUTH_USER_MODEL. When logging in with Google openid for example, everything works fine, I can associate the socialauth user with my custom user model and its ID gets saved in the session.

Now on the next request, when the session/auth middelwares kick in, it finds the correct ID and backend from the session and calls get_user(request, user_id) to get the user. It looks like get_user() is not overridden in SocialAuthBackend so the default (from ModelBackend) is taken. This default one is hardwared to use the django.contrib.auth User model.

Does it make sense to override get_user() in SocialAuthBackend so it takes into account the custom user model? I tried it with a quick hack (overriding and hardcoding to my user model) and it seems to be logging in the correct user now.

    #my quick hack in SocialAuthBackend
    def get_user(self, user_id):
        try:
            return EndUser.objects.get(pk=user_id) 
        except EndUser.DoesNotExist:
            return None

I must authenticate in separate way users and external applications, for this i use two different blueprints.
```python
@api_users.before_request
@jwt_required
@user_loader
def before_request():
    pass

@api_external_apps.before_request
@jwt_required
@external_apps_loader
def before_request():
    pass
```
But the user_claims_loader is global to all the app and i use different identities for users and apps.

How can i solve this ?

